## Project Overview
During my MECOP internship with Daimler Truck North America (DTNA), I worked within the Advanced Vehicle Systems department on the **SuperTruck 3 Program**—a U.S. Department of Energy-funded initiative to develop hydrogen fuel cell-powered heavy-duty sleeper cabs. I was responsible for delivering manufacturing-ready designs and thermal system integrations for both the "B-Sample" prototype and the "Final Demonstrator" vehicle.

### Key Engineering Contributions
* **Evaporative Cooling Tank Redesign:** Redesigned a high-cost plastic cooling tank into a welded aluminum assembly. By utilizing COTS (Commercial Off-The-Shelf) components, I simplified the supply chain and achieved a **$300 per-unit cost reduction**. 
* **Complex Fluid Routing:** Utilized the **Siemens NX Routing** application to resolve a 3-4mm interference issue between primary coolant lines and the chassis crossmember. Successfully re-pathed the lines while maintaining a strict 70mm minimum bend radius and a 6mm hood clearance constraint.
* **Radiator Airflow Optimization:** Engineered six TPV anti-recirculation baffles to optimize airflow through the radiator stack, completing full CAD and design release within a one-week deadline to meet a critical program "Design Freeze."
* **Subsystem Component Design:** Handled rapid prototyping and design release for various support components, including custom flowmeter brackets, pump mounts, and high-voltage battery surge tanks.

### Tools & Industry Standards
* **Software:** Siemens NX (Solid Modeling, Sheet Metal, Routing, Drafting, FEA).
* **Standards:** Produced manufacturing-ready documentation and full technical packages utilizing **ASME Y14.5 GD&T** standards.
* **Cross-Functional Collaboration:** Coordinated directly with Chassis and Airflow specialists to resolve multidisciplinary design conflicts prior to manufacturing.

